article.headline: Bulldogs commit season-high 26 turnovers in win
article.linkText: Despite turnovers, Mississippi State rolls over Jackson St.
article.story:
STARKVILLE, Miss. (AP) -- It wasn't a pretty win for Mississippi
State.

	   Timmy Bowers scored 18 points to lead the 24th-ranked Bulldogs,
who committed a season-high 26 turnovers, to a 71-56 victory over
Jackson State on Wednesday night in the first meeting between the
instate schools since the 1985-86 season.

	   The Bulldogs (4-1) won the previous two by a combined 46 points,
including a 77-62 decision in the most recent matchup on Nov. 30,
1985.

	   Mississippi State expected an easy win over the Tigers (0-5),
who lost their first game at Arkansas by 42 points.

	   "That was not one of our better efforts out there tonight,''
Mississippi State coach Rick Stansbury said. "Naturally, you're
happy to win but I was not happy with the way we won. From the tip,
we were not as sharp mentally.''

	   Mississippi State was playing its third game in five days.

	   "We knew that this game wasn't going to be easy,'' Bowers said.
"We're tired. Everybody's tired, but we can't use that as an
excuse.''

	   Jackson State trailed by 20 points with 9:29 remaining before
the Tigers went on a 7-2 run with Tim Henderson scoring six points,
including a 3-pointer that made it 57-42.

	   Henderson led the Tigers with 17 points.

	   Mississippi State built the lead back up to 62-42 on a layup by
Ontario Harper before Jackson State went on an 11-3 run. Cliff
Walker hit a 3-pointer with 3:47 left as the Tigers cut the lead to
65-53.

	   That was as close as it would get.

	   "We didn't shoot the ball well and neither did they so that's
why we sort of hung around,'' Jackson State coach Andy Stoglin
said. "If we shoot the ball well then we could have really made it
a game.''

	   Jackson State shot 27.6 from the field, while Mississippi State
made 48 percent.

	   Mario Austin was with the team hours after his attorneys and
lawyers from Mississippi State made a presentation to the NCAA,
hoping it will free the junior center to play his first game of the
season.

	   The NCAA Clearinghouse had declared Austin eligible to play as a
freshman in 2000. The NCAA took a second look recently at Austin's
records from Sumter County High School in York, Ala., and a
committee told Mississippi State two weeks ago that two courses
Austin took in the ninth and 10th grades should not have counted
toward his freshman eligibility.

	   Mississippi State expects to learn the NCAA's final decision by
next week.

	   "They met in Indianapolis today and nothing has been resolved
yet,'' Stansbury said. "We think there was some positive
movement.''

	   Mississippi State scored 28 of its 37 first-half points in the
paint. Jackson State had trouble with the Bulldogs' man-to-man
defense, shooting 27.6 percent in the first half, including 3-of-14
from the 3-point line.

	   Branden Vincent had 11 points and nine rebounds for Mississippi
State, while Marcus Campbell had 10 points and Harper had a
career-high 10 rebounds.
	   
Mississippi State is 29-3 at home against non-conference
opponents under Stansbury.
